On Arch Linux, you have two main ways to install npm: the "standard" way through the official repositories and the "flexible" way using a version manager.

While npm is the industry standard, there are indeed more "wonderful" modern alternatives—specifically pnpm and Bun—that offer better speed and disk efficiency without sacrificing compatibility.

1. The Standard Install (The "Quick" Way)
If you just want npm and don't care about managing multiple versions of Node.js, run:

Bash
sudo pacman -S nodejs npm
Note: Arch splits nodejs and npm into two packages, unlike many other distros.

Pro Tip: Never use sudo npm install -g. It can mess up your system files. If you need global packages, either use a version manager (below) or configure a user-local prefix.

2. The Modern Standard: nvm or fnm
Most Arch users prefer a Node Version Manager. This lets you install Node/npm in your home directory (no sudo needed) and switch versions instantly.

Install nvm (Node Version Manager):

Bash
sudo pacman -S nvm
echo 'source /usr/share/nvm/init-nvm.sh' >> ~/.bashrc  # Or ~/.zshrc
source ~/.bashrc
nvm install --lts
Modern Alternative: fnm (Fast Node Manager). It’s written in Rust and is significantly faster than nvm. You can find it in the AUR: yay -S fnm-bin.

3. The "Wonderful" Alternatives
If you find npm slow or hate how node_modules eats your disk space, these two are the top choices in 2026:

pnpm (The "Efficient" Choice)
pnpm is widely considered the best successor to npm. It uses "hard links" to share one global version of a package across all your projects.

Why it's better: It saves massive amounts of disk space and is 2-3x faster than npm.

Compatibility: 100%. It uses the same package.json and works with almost every library.

Install: sudo pacman -S pnpm (or corepack enable pnpm).

Bun (The "Speed Demon")
Bun is a modern runtime (like Node) that includes its own package manager.

Why it's better: It is absurdly fast (up to 20x faster than npm for some tasks). It also replaces nodemon, jest, and tsc in many workflows.

Compatibility: Excellent (~98%+), though very niche native C++ modules occasionally have issues.

Install: curl -fsSL https://bun.sh/install | bash.

Comparison at a Glance
Feature	npm	pnpm	Bun
Speed	Average	Fast	Blazing Fast
Disk Usage	Heavy (duplicates)	Low (shared)	Low (shared)
Compatibility	100% (The Standard)	High	Very High
Best For	Legacy/Simple projects	Monorepos / Every day	Speed / New Apps
My recommendation: If you want a drop-in replacement that just works better, go with pnpm. If you want the absolute cutting edge of speed, try Bun.

