You hit the nail on the head. That is the fundamental trade-off in the JavaScript ecosystem right now.

Here is the breakdown of why Bun is faster but carries more "risk" compared to pnpm.

1. Speed: Why Bun Wins
Bun is written in Zig (a low-level language like C++) and uses the JavaScriptCore engine (from Safari) instead of V8 (from Chrome/Node).

Zero-Overhead: When you run bun install, it doesn’t have to "spin up" the entire Node.js runtime just to read a text file. It’s a native binary that does one thing very fast.

Binary Lockfiles: Bun uses a binary format for its lockfile (bun.lockb), which it can parse almost instantly compared to the massive YAML or JSON files used by pnpm and npm.

Parallelism: It’s designed from the ground up to use every core of your CPU simultaneously during installation.

2. Compatibility: Why pnpm is "Safer"
pnpm is built on top of Node.js. It doesn't try to reinvent the engine; it just fixes how files are stored on your disk.

100% Node Native: Since pnpm still runs on Node, it has zero "runtime" compatibility issues. If a package works in Node, it works with pnpm.

The "Symlink" Edge: pnpm uses a clever system of hard links and symlinks. It stores one copy of a package in a global folder and links it into your project. This is very stable and recognized by almost all dev tools (VS Code, ESLint, etc.).

Bun's "95% Reality": Bun is incredibly compatible, but it’s a re-implementation of Node. In 2026, it handles roughly 95-99% of the Node API. That last 1% usually involves:

Native C++ Addons: Packages that compile low-level code (like some older database drivers or image processing libs) sometimes fail in Bun.

Internal Node APIs: If a library relies on a very obscure, undocumented part of Node.js, Bun might not have copied that behavior exactly yet.

