Gemini said
You are thinking of "Environment Pollution" and "System Conflicts." You likely heard that using sudo npm install -g is a bad idea, and you’re 100% correct. On Arch Linux specifically, doing this can actually break your OS because npm might overwrite a file that pacman (your system manager) thinks it owns.

Here is exactly what you are remembering and why the modern "wonderful" ways solve it.

1. The "System Conflict" Problem
When you use sudo npm install -g, Node tries to put files into /usr/bin/ or /usr/lib/.

The Risk: Arch's pacman also manages those folders. If npm and pacman fight over the same file name, your next system update might fail, or worse, your Node installation will become "corrupted" and impossible to uninstall cleanly.

The Fix: Never use sudo with npm, pnpm, or bun.

2. The "Global Mess" Problem
Even without sudo, if you install 50 different tools globally, they all share one hidden folder in your home directory.

The Risk: If Tool A needs "Library X" version 1.0, and Tool B needs version 2.0, they will fight. One of them will stop working.

The Fix: Use pnpm or npx/bunx.

The "Wonderful" Modern Solutions
To avoid the "Global is Bad" trap while still having the Gemini CLI available everywhere, use one of these two "clean" methods:

Method A: Use a Version Manager (The Gold Standard)
If you use fnm or nvm, "Global" packages are installed inside a specific folder in your /home/user/ directory.

They are invisible to the rest of the system.

pacman doesn't even know they exist.

It is safe and the preferred way for developers.

Method B: Use pnpm (The Efficient Middle Ground)
pnpm is smarter than npm. Even when you install "globally" (-g), it uses a content-addressable store.

It doesn't actually copy the files over and over; it just creates a "link."

It’s much harder to "break" your environment with pnpm than with standard npm.

Method C: Use npx or bunx (The "Cleanest" Way)
If you don't want to "install" it at all, just run:

Bash
bunx @google/gemini-cli
This downloads the CLI to a temporary folder, runs it, and essentially forgets it. No global pollution, no conflicts, no mess.

The Verdict:
You’re right to be wary of -g. If you want Gemini permanently, the "Arch Way" is to install fnm (via AUR) or pnpm (via pacman), which keeps your global tools isolated and safe.

